result.execSummary:
The defendant Elaine Ann Hagan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

judgments.action: Guilty Due to No Contest Plea

charges.dispoDesc: Guilty Due to No Contest Plea

result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Elaine Ann Hagan

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Elaine Ann Hagan in court.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Atty Hendee states that an offer was provided at the pre-trial conference; in speaking with the defendant before court, she would like to accept that offer.
  Atty Hendee states plea agreement.    Court advises defendant of right to an attorney.  Defendant waives their right to an attorney and enters a No Contest plea.
  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.
  Atty Hendee relies on the criminal complaint for a factual basis.

  BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and finds defendant guilty.

Atty Hendee asks the court to follow the joint recommendation.
Defendant asks for 90 days to pay.

BY THE COURT:  Pay fine and costs = $379.00.
bond to be applied
60 days to pay the balance

Atty Hendee states that there also is a traffic case 15TR65; the State moves to dismiss.
BY THE COURT:  15TR65 is dismissed.

Defendant Elaine Ann Hagan in court.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  Defendant received a copy of the criminal complaint.  Court advises defendant of right to an attorney.  BY THE COURT:  Court enters a Not Guilty plea on behalf of the defendant.
  Defendant waives their right to an attorney in order to have a conference with the District Attorney.  Court questions defendant on her waiver of counsel.  BY THE COURT:  Court finds waiver made freely, voluntarily and intelligently.
BY THE COURT:  Bond continued.  Return date scheduled for May 7, 2015 at 03:30 pm.
